-EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I thought the power grid was a closed system? How the heck is it connected to the Internet?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Yes, the power grid is a closed system, but the servers, switches, and routers that the company places on the wires are not. The powerlines only act a communication lines, nothing more. The only things the powerlines act as are a communication wire. There are many many problems with this type of connection. A few are quite obvious. First is the cost. This type of connection can cost as much as 10 times the price of a cable or DSL provider. This is because of the cost of upkeep. Secondly, Servers are frequently down, and weather damage can be brutal. Some providers are even giving a small amount of dial up to compensate for the downtime. Third is signal strength. Due to high noise on powerlines, actual connection strength can vary greatly. Only late at night when the power company lowers power output will you get max bandwidth. <br>
<br>
